</div></div></div></td>
</tr><tr><td style="padding:0.3em 0.4em 0.3em;font-weight:bold;border-top: 1px solid #aaa; border-bottom: 1px solid #aaa;padding-top: 0.1em; font-weight: bold;">
<a href="/wiki/Portal:Politics" title="Portal:Politics">Politics Portal</a></td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:right;font-size:115%;padding-top: 0.6em;"><div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Politics_sidebar" title="Template:Politics sidebar"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Politics_sidebar" title="Template talk:Politics sidebar"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Politics_sidebar&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Sovereignty</b> is the full right and power of a governing body over itself, without any interference from outside sources or bodies. In political theory, sovereignty is a <a href="/wiki/Substantive" class="mw-redirect" title="Substantive">substantive</a> term designating supreme <a href="/wiki/Authority" title="Authority">authority</a> over some <a href="/wiki/Polity" title="Polity">polity</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-britannica_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-britannica-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2>Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>
